text.tspan: These two lines validate that at least 100x the base fee has been fed in
to feed the contract. (Request that it be executed.) The alternate is not
to do this, and have your contract stop when it runs out of funds.
There is a one-time initialisation of this contract which is marked in storage location 1000.
This number 1000 is arbitrary, but needs to be high enough not to overwrite
the contract code which resides in the same storage space.
tx.data is a psuedoarray that acts like parameters in a function call to our contract
The idea is that if someone wants to send X currency units to
account A in currency contract C, they will need to make a
transaction of the form (C, 100 * block.basefee, [A, X])
Not doing this check would allow mutations to our own code.
Not enough funds in from address
mycreator is a constant set when this contract is compiled. It allows the
currency creator to have 10^18 units of currency when its first initialized.
Line 15 makes it so this code is only executed once.
